'''Conrad Brunner''' (31 August 1859 in [[Diessenhofen]] &ndash; 8 June 1927 in [[Zurich]]) was a [[Switzerland|Swiss]] physician, surgeon and medical historian. He was particularly concerned with the disinfection of wounds and their healing.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|title=Brunner, Conrad|editor-first=Clarence Lewis|editor-last=Barnhart|encyclopedia=The New Century Cyclopedia of Names|publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts |year=1954|volume=1|pages=683&ndash;684|oclc=174347730}}</ref>

Brunner came from a family of Swiss physicians and pharmacists, among whom was [[Johann Conrad Brunner]].<ref name="HLS">{{Cite web|author=Koelbing, Huldrych M. F.|title=Geschichte: Brunner, Conrad (History: Brunner, Conrad)|language=German|publisher=Historischen Lexikon der Schweiz|url=http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D14306.php|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130317204210/http://www.hls-dhs-dss.ch/textes/d/D14306.php|archivedate=17 March 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref> His father, John Brunner, was a physician and botanist.<ref name="HLS" /> Brunner received medical degrees from the [[University of Zurich]] and the [[Leipzig University|University of Leipzig]], and went on to receive an advanced [[academic degree]] of Doctor of Medicine in 1885.<ref name="HLS" /> He then completed his practical surgeon training studying under [[Rudolf Ulrich Krönlein]].<ref name="HLS" />  Beginning in 1888 he took a series of trips to noted surgeries, studying under [[Theodor Billroth]] at the [[University of Vienna]], [[Ernst von Bergmann]] at [[Humboldt University of Berlin]], and other surgeons at the University of Leipzig, the [[Dresden University of Technology|University of Dresden]] and the [[Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich|University of Münich]]. In 1888, with the third volume in 1889, he published his ''Erfahrungen und Studien über Wundinfektion und Wundbehandlung''.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Brunner, Conrad|year=1898|title=Erfahrungen und Studien über Wundinfektion und Wundbehandlung (Experiences and studies on wound infection and wound care)|publisher=J. Huber|location=Frauenfeld, Switzerland|oclc=14781957}}</ref>

==Life==
In 1889 Brunner married Clara Margot<ref name="HLS" /> and opened a private practice in Zurich, with [[Hospital privileges|privileges]] at a number of nearby hospitals. Beginning in 1890 he served as an [[Professor#Tenured_and_tenure-track_positions|associate professor]] of surgery at the University of Zurich, relinquishing the position in 1897.<ref name="HLS" />  From 1896 to 1922 he served as the chief physician at the Cantonal Hospital in [[Münsterlingen]].<ref name="Benoist-Prize">{{Cite web|title=Past laureates: 1921 Conrad Brunner|publisher=The Marcel Benoist Foundation|url=http://www.marcel-benoist.ch/en/the-prize/past-laureates/detail/?id=2|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130317195528/http://www.marcel-benoist.ch/en/the-prize/past-laureates/detail/?id=2|archivedate=17 March 2013|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|author=Studer, Karl and Ammann, Jürg|year=1990|title=150 Jahre Münsterlingen: Das Thurgauische Kantonsspital und die Psychiatrische Klinik, 1840-1990|location=|publisher=Thurgauisches Kantonsspital|oclc=716678070}}</ref> In 1922 he was the co-founder of the Thurgauisch-Schaffhausischen Pulmonary Sanatorium in [[Davos]], primarily for [[tuberculosis]] sufferers. 

==Work==
Conrad Brunner conducted and published clinical, bacteriological and experimental studies on the effectiveness of various contemporary wound disinfection methods. He was able to prove that his method, namely the ''Brunner's Jodalkoholdesinfektion'', offered by far the best guarantee against the occurrence of wound diseases. 

Brunner researched and published on topics in the history of medicine, mostly as related to Switzerland.

